Part 2: Pre-Process¶

Q1: Methods to Solve Missing Values Problem in Dataset¶

A. Deletion of missing values

B. Impute by Average(mean,mode,linear regression)

C. Impute by Predictive Model(Decision Tree, KNN, Random Forest, etc.)

Imputation of missing values is a tricky subject and unless the missing data is not observed completely at random, imputing such missing values by a Predictive Model is highly desirable since it can lead to better insights and overall increase in performance of the predictive models.

Q2: Missing Values in diabetes Dataset & Solving them¶

Most missing value rates among features belongs to these features:

  • DiabetesPedigreeFunction with 23.177 %
  • SkinThickness with 18.75 %
  • Pregnancies with 17.317 %
In [ ]:
import numpy as np
zero_not_accepted = ['Glucose','BloodPressure','SkinThickness','BMI','Insulin']
for column in zero_not_accepted:
    data[column] = data[column].replace(0,np.NaN)
    mean = int(data[column].mean(skipna=True))
    data[column] = data[column].replace(np.NaN,mean)
    
data['DiabetesPedigreeFunction'] = data['DiabetesPedigreeFunction'].fillna(data['DiabetesPedigreeFunction'].mean())
data['Pregnancies'] = data['Pregnancies'].fillna(data['Pregnancies'].mean())
data['Age'] = data['Age'].fillna(data['Age'].mean())
Q3: Purpose of normalization in numerical features¶

Normalization ensures that the features we use in computations are not affected by trivial variations like height, width, scaling factors, orientations etc. Bringing the data values to a specific range makes them independent of these factors e.g. normalizing a series of lengths to the range [0, 1] means they are nor affected by scaling factors as absolute values are now converted to ratios.

In this project, we better use the normalization for better performance.

Q4: What pre-processes works on categorical features¶

There are two types of categorical features.
I. Categorial
II. Ordinal : special case of categorical feature but with values sorted in some meaningful order.

We can use the following encodings:

  • Label Encoding : It basically replaces the unique values of categorical features with numbers.
  • Frequency Encoding : It maps unique values to their frequencies.
  • One-Hot Encoding : It creates new columns for each unique value of a categorical feature and assigns 1 or 0 to each row based on the value of the feature.\

Label encoding and Frequency encoding are often used for tree-based methods while One-Hot encoding is often used for non-tree-based-methods.

Q5: Is it possible to remove some columns¶

Yes, we can remove some columns. But, we should be careful about the columns that we remove.
There are some cases that we can remove a column from the dataset:

  • We can remove the columns that have a high correlation with other columns.
  • We can remove the columns that have a low correlation with the target column.
  • We can remove the columns that have a high number of missing values or unique values.
Q6: How to divide datas into train dataset and test dataset¶

The most common split ratio is 80:20. But as long as underfitting and overfitting are not a problem, the split ratio can be changed.

Q7: Validation¶

In validation we use set of examples used to tune the parameters of a classifier.
Validation dataset is the sample of data used to provide an unbiased evaluation of a model fit on the training dataset while tuning model hyperparameters. The evaluation becomes more biased as skill on the validation dataset is incorporated into the model configuration.

Decision Tree Learning¶
In [ ]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
depths = range(1, 30)

test = []
train = []

for i in depths:
    tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=i)
    tree.fit(X_train,y_train)

    train_pred= tree.predict(X_train)
    train.append(accuracy_score(y_train, train_pred))

    test_pred = tree.predict(X_test)
    test.append(accuracy_score(y_test, test_pred))

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.plot(depths, train, label='Train')
plt.plot(depths, test, label='Test')
plt.legend()
plt.title('Accuracy according to depths')
plt.show()

We choose depth = 5 to avoid underfitting and overfitting.

In [ ]:
leaves = range(1, 30)

test = []
train = []

for i in leaves:
    tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=4, min_samples_leaf=i)
    tree.fit(X_train,y_train)

    train_pred= tree.predict(X_train)
    train.append(accuracy_score(y_train, train_pred))

    test_pred = tree.predict(X_test)
    test.append(accuracy_score(y_test, test_pred))

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 10))
plt.plot(depths, train, label='Train')
plt.plot(depths, test, label='Test')
plt.legend()
plt.title('Accuracy according to min_samples')
plt.show()

Q3: Overfittng & Underfitting¶

Overfitting : When a model is too complex for the given data, it will learn the noise in the data and will not be able to generalize well on the test data.
Underfitting : When a model is too simple for the given data, it will not be able to learn the underlying patterns in the data and will not be able to generalize well on the test data.

Q1: Random Forest Hyperparameters¶
  • n_estimators : The number of trees in the forest.
  • max_features : The number of features to consider when looking for the best split.
  • max_depth : The maximum depth of the tree.
  • min_samples_split : The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
  • min_samples_leaf : The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.
  • bootstrap : Whether bootstrap samples are used when building trees.

Q2: Compare Random Forest to Decision Tree¶

Bias : Bias is the difference between the expected prediction of our model and the correct value which we are trying to predict.
Variance : Variance is the amount that the estimate of the target function will change if different training data was used.

Different Combinations of Bias-Variance :

  • Low-Bias, Low-Variance:\

The combination of low bias and low variance shows an ideal machine learning model. However, it is not possible practically.

  • High-Bias, Low-Variance:\

The combination of high bias and low variance shows an underfitting model.

  • Low-Bias, High-Variance:\

The combination of low bias and high variance shows an overfitting model.

  • High-Bias, High-Variance:\

The combination of high bias and high variance shows a very complex model.

Random Forest is a combination of Decision Trees. So, we can compare them based on their bias and variance.

  • Bias: Random Forest has a higher bias than Decision Tree.
  • Variance: Random Forest has a lower variance than Decision Tree.
